OVERFITTING. The proposed patch attempts to fix the bug by filtering neighbors to keep only the minimum edge cost per neighbor before pushing them onto the heap, but this does not address the fundamental flaw in the algorithm's logic. The core issue is that the algorithm prematurely marks nodes as "queued" and never revisits them even if a cheaper path is found later, violating the principle of Dijkstra's algorithm which requires updating tentative distances and re-adding nodes to the priority queue when a better path is discovered. Simply choosing the minimum edge cost per neighbor at each step does not guarantee that the overall shortest path is found, especially in graphs where cheaper paths emerge after initially exploring more expensive edges. Therefore, the patch superficially filters edges but does not fix the critical problem of handling multiple paths and updating distances, so it is an overfitting fix that may pass the given tests but will fail on more complex graphs exhibiting the described bug.
